<solution id="id1172402568517">
<para id="element-44">
The bodies acquire equal angular velocity due to friction operating between the surfaces in contact. However, friction here is internal to the system of two rotating disks. Thus, there is no external torque on the system and we can employ law of conservation of angular momentum :
</para>
<para id="element-44a">
<figure id="fig-44a">
<title> Two rotating disks </title>
<media id="id1172408353187" alt=""><image src="../../media/caq2.gif" mime-type="image/gif"/></media>
<caption> Two disks are brought in contact along common axis of rotation.</caption>
</figure>
</para>

<para id="element-45">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
<m:mtr>
<m:mtd>
<m:msub>
<m:mi> L </m:mi>
<m:mi> i </m:mi>
</m:msub>
<m:mo> = </m:mo> 
<m:msub>
<m:mi> L </m:mi>
<m:mi> f </m:mi>
</m:msub>
</m:mtd>
</m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</para>
<para id="element-46">
Here,
</para>
<para id="element-47">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
<m:mtr>
<m:mtd>
<m:msub>
<m:mi> L </m:mi>
