</m:mrow>
</m:mfrac>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mi> (d) </m:mi>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mfrac>
<m:mrow>
<m:mn> 4 </m:mn>
<m:mi> L </m:mi>
</m:mrow>
<m:mrow>
<m:mn> 3 </m:mn>
<m:mi> v </m:mi>
</m:mrow>
</m:mfrac>
</m:mtd>
</m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</para>
</problem>
<solution id="id1172394082742">

<para id="element-72">The line of action of the force on the block due to obstruction passes through the axis of rotation about which block suddenly rotates i.e. about the obstruction for a brief period. These forces (operating at the time of collision) do not constitute torque. We can, therefore, conclude that there is no torque on the block. According to law of conservation of angular momentum,
</para>
<para id="element-73">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
<m:mtr>
<m:mtd>
<m:msub>
<m:mi> L </m:mi>
